Throughout the landlocked state of Bolivia, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources in the 19th century is still strong, as is the longing to sail on the Pacific again.
The hopes may be at their peak for decades, while Bolivia awaits a judgment of the International Court of Justice on 1 October, after five years of voting.
"Bolivia has momentum, a sense of community and clarity, and naturally waits with a positive look at the outcome," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the ruling of the International Court on large screens throughout the country and hope that the Hague Court will agree that Chile – after decades of discussion – is committed to negotiating to give Bolivia sovereignty over an area of access to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, who is facing a controversial election campaign next year, also has a lot at stake at the trial on Monday.
"We are close to returning to the Pacific," he promised at the end of August.
But analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will take Bolivia’s side – and that there would not be much change if it did.
The UN Assembly, which is based in the Netherlands, does not have the power to take over Chilean territory and has stipulated that it cannot determine the outcome of possible discussions.
That the International Court of Justice gives judgment only six months after the final arguments were heard indicates that the case was "not complicated", said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And instead of furthering Bolivia's cause, the last four years may have returned.
"The case of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian leadership," Zárate said.
She said that Morales' warlike rhetoric has ended the remaining Chilean goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will eventually continue the discussions, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
