John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools have many impressive academic achievements behind them, and this is still in 2018 with yet another outstanding exam results, which are even strengthened by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other efforts in the local environment.
With up to 30,000 students around Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools are trying to prepare their pupils for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can put together and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we find that modern languages remain a popular topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it hits his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it'll hit the heart."
It is an important reminder that we cannot just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust among people from other countries.
We can see from the latest exam results this year that languages are highest in the statistics with the most passed exams in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students studying foreign languages received the high grade A.
The data collected by the 74 member schools of the CIS showed that 72 percent of the students were graded A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important competences that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now perceived as subject choices at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools' curricula and elsewhere.
A study carried out by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that among the reasons why employers could not fill vacancies, 17 % had to do with lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
More job opportunities in the future will require language skills, and these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Whatever career they choose, if they have learned another language, they have a great advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person a head start to competitors.
According to a YouGov poll of over 4,000 polls in Britain in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a multi-digit percentage, 15 percent.
That is why it is important to invest in language teaching for those who are children today.
When you can speak more languages, especially those from developing countries, you give children a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, there is a difference between schools in which languages are taught.
A number of schools focus on the more classic modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be most important for the UK by looking towards 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
At present, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be really important for the future of the country in a global business environment, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this distinction to Scotland's youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
