North Korea says they won't disarm unilaterally if there's no trust.
On Saturday, North Korea's Foreign Minister told the UN that continued sanctions reinforce their distrust of the United States and that it will not abandon their nuclear weapons unilaterally under such conditions.
Ri Yong Ho told the General Assembly of the worldwide organisation that North Korea had shown "significant goodwill" within the last year, for example by stopping nuclear and missile tests, running an area for nuclear tests and promising not to develop nuclear weapons and technology further.
"However, we have not seen a similar reaction from the United States," he said.
"Without confidence in the United States, there is no confidence in our national security and under such conditions there is no chance that we ourselves will take the first step and disarm unilaterally."
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phased" approach to nuclear disarmament, where North Korea would be rewarded if they took gradual steps. However, his speech seemed important as it did not unequivocally reject unilateral disarmament, as it had previously been the case with Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit ever between a incumbent US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on 12 June, where Kim promised to work "nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula", while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has asked for a formal end to the Korean war, which took place in 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first abandon their nuclear weapons.
Washington has also shown resistance to softening international sanctions against North Korea.
"The US insists on 'nuclear disarmament first' and extends the pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose by coercion and even opposes 'the declaration of the end of the war'", Ri said.
"The notion that the sanctions can bring us down is a dream among people who do not know who we are.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions reinforce our distrust."
Ri did not mention any plans for another summit between Kim and Trump, as the American leader highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the Minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and the South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months and added: "If nuclear disarmament were to be negotiated with South Korea and not the United States, the negotiations would not be so bogged down."
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri's speech was very different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that firing North Korea's rockets against the American mainland was inevitable after "Mr Evil President" Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on suicide mission.
Last year in the United Nations, Trump threatened 'total destruction' of North Korea, but this year he praised Kim for showing courage in terms of disarmament, but said that there is still much to be done and that sanctions have to remain until North Korea disarms.
Wednesday Trump said he didn't have a schedule for these actions, but said "It doesn't matter whether it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that: "The Security Council must maintain sanctions with conviction and without error until we achieve the total, final, confirmed nuclear disarmament."
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously increased economic sanctions against North Korea in an attempt to stop Pyongyang's missile and nuclear weapons programme.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines during the UN General Assembly and subsequently said that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for another meeting.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times during the year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July and said that progress had been made, while North Korea, just hours later, accused him of making "gangsy demands."
At a meeting with Moon this month North Korea promised to shut down a missile plant and a nuclear complex if the United States took "equivalent steps."
He said that Kim had told him that the "corresponding steps" he demanded were the security promises given by Trump in Singapore, as well as moves towards normalization of relations with Washington.
Students at Harvard take a course to get enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University has given all bachelor students more sleep. The purpose of the course is to counteract the growing macho culture, where you study all night kept up with large amounts of caffeine.
One researcher has shown that students at the world's best university often have no idea the first thing about taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, has completed the course which he thinks is the first of his kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a paper on what effects sleep deprivation has on learning.
"When the presentation was finished, a girl came up to me and said, "Why am I only told this now when I'm on the candidate?"
"She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is offered for the first time this year, explains how good sleeping habits can improve your academic and sporting performance as well as your overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the university's health area, says that the university has decided to offer the course after finding out that the students were in severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course consists of various interactive exercises.
In one of the exercises there is a picture of a dorm room where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, and how your sporting performance is affected by lack of sleep and how important good sleeping habits are.
In another part of the course, participants hear about how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attacks, blood clots, depression and cancer.
Participants are encouraged to think about their daily habits by clicking on different icons on an interactive map of campus.
"We know that it will not change students' behaviour immediately.
But we think they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect health", adds Professor Czeisler.
The pride of taking an "all-nighter" still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and increased pressure on students have led to sleep deprivation as a growing problem.
The "secret weapon" against stress, exhaustion and anxiety is good and sufficient sleep, he said – it even counteracts weight gain, because lack of sleep makes the brain think that you are starving, why they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californiar who studied chemical and physical biology, last year helped Professor Czeisler organize the course when he took one of his courses at his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and got him to work on making it a general course throughout the university.
He hopes that the next thing will be that all graduates are offered a similar course before they continue their education.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm so that they know when to go to bed and when to go up. This can create awareness of the harmful effects of the light from electronic screens, which can move at the circadian rhythm and make it harder to fall asleep.
