What is the Global Citizens Festival and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
On Saturday, New York hosts the Global Citizens Festival – an annual music festival with a very impressive range of artists and an equally impressive goal; to end world poverty.
For the seventh time, the Global Citizens Festival will receive tens of thousands of people on Central Park’s large lawn, where they can look forward to concerts with Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes. At the same time, the festival will raise awareness of the real goal, which is to end extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival started in 2012 and is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international interest organisation that is struggling to end poverty by increasing the number of active opponents.
To receive a free ticket to the event (if you do not want to pay for a VIP ticket), concertgoers must perform a number of tasks or "actions". For example, do volunteer work, write to a world leader, make a phone call or some other meaningful action that can raise awareness about the goal of ending poverty.
But how successful has Global Citizen been now that they have 12 years left to reach the goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert real change, or is it just another case of so-called "clicktivism" – i.e. people feel that they make a difference by signing a petition online or making a Twitter look?
Global Citizen reports that since 2011, they have recorded more than 19 million "actions" from their members aimed at various goals.
They believe that these actions have encouraged world leaders to make binding goals and policies that correspond to more than 37 billion dollars, which by 2030 are expected to have affected more than 2.25 billion people.
At the beginning of 2018, the group listed 390 objectives and actions that had been created because of their actions, which amounted to over $10 billion, which had already been paid or collected.
The group estimates that so far these funds have had a direct impact on almost 649 million people worldwide.
One of the main objectives is The Power of Nutrition, which has started in England and is a collaboration between investors and active people. They strive to "help children live out their full potential" and promise 35 million dollars to alleviate nutrition problems in Rwanda after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
"With the help of the British government, donors, governments of other countries and world citizens like you, the social injustice of malnutrition can become a footnote in the history books," said the ambassador for The Power of Nutrition, Tracey Ullman, to the audience at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that the UK Government has now promised funds to improve the nutrition of mothers and children after receiving more than 5,000 calls online. This project, Power of Nutrition, will help five million mothers and children with advice on nutrition.
In answer to one of the website's frequently asked questions, saying: "What makes you think we can end extreme poverty?",
Global Citizen wrote: "It will be a long and hard struggle, and sometimes we will stumble and make mistakes.
But as with the civil rights movement and the movements against apartheid, we will succeed because we are stronger together."
Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe are among the performers at this year's festival in New York. Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman will be hosts.
