Germany’s new warship is being postponed again
The German Navy's latest frigate should have been ready in 2014 to replace warships from the Cold War. However, the Germans must wait at least a year yet due to technical problems and an escalating price, reports local media.
The insertion of the largest ship into the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg class of frigates, "Rheinland-Pfalz", has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quotes a military spokesman.
The ship was supposed to be part of the fleet in 2014, but after delivery problems have plagued the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ordered back in 2007 are to replace the ageing frigates of the Bremen class.
They are known to have a powerful cannon, a wide range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as stealth technologies such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Another important feature of the latest frigates is a smaller need for maintenance: it should be possible to have frigates away from home ports for up to two years.
But the repeated delays mean that the advanced warships – which are said to make Germany appear to be an overseas power factor – will already be obsolete when they are deployed, Die Zeit writes.
The failed F125 frigate created headlines last year when the German fleet officially refused to take the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy returned a ship to the shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media mentioned a number of crucial "software and hardware errors" that made the warship useless in combat situations.
Software failures were of particular importance as the ships of the Baden-Wuertemberg class must be controlled by a crew of 120 sailors – that is only half the crew of the older Bremen frigates.
It also turned out that the ship was too heavy, reducing its performance and limiting the fleet's ability for future updates.
The 7000 ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is said to be twice as heavy as similar ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to hardware errors, the cost of the project, which includes staff training, is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached staggering €3.1 billion ($3.6 billion), with an initial price of €2.2 billion.
The problems with the latest frigates are becoming even more important in the light of recent warnings that Germany's naval power is shrinking.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German Government's Defence Committee, admitted earlier this year that the fleet "is running out of ready-to-lay ships."
