National Trust Sniping Into Bats’ Secret Life
New research from an area in the Highlands of Scotland is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hope is that the findings will shed light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and will help in the work on future conservation efforts.
The study is conducted by scientists from the Scottish National Trust and follows ordinary bats, dwarf bats, long-eared bats and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed in carefully selected locations in the area to record the activities of the bats during the season.
Data are also collected by staff from NTS and volunteers using handheld detectors.
In-depth analysis of the sound recordings will reveal the bat call frequencies and show which species does what.
To produce a detailed landscape picture of their behaviour, a report and map of the habitat are made.
Nature conservation advisor to NTS Rob Dewar hopes that the results reveal which areas of the habitat are most important and how they are used by the different species.
This knowledge can help determine the benefits of habitat conservation interventions such as the establishment of meadows, and how best to preserve forest areas for bats and similar species.
The number of bats in Scotland and Britain has fallen dramatically over the last 100 years.
They are threatened by buildings and urban enlargement projects which affect the shipowners and restrict their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a danger, as can fly traps, chemical treatment of building materials, and attacks from pets.
Bats aren't actually blind.
But because they primarily hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes.
They use an advanced echolocation technique to find insects and fly around obstacles.
NTS, which is responsible for the preservation of more than 270 historical buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten trained experts who often collect data, inspect nests and sometimes perform rescue operations.
The organization has even made Scotland’s first and only dedicated bat reserve in the area around Three in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten of Scotland’s bat species.
The area's caretaker, David Thompson, says it's an ideal territory for them.
"Here at Three we have a very good area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and the whole good habitat.
There's a lot you don't know about bats, so work here and elsewhere can help you understand what they need to thrive."
He stresses the importance of looking for bats before carrying out maintenance tasks on properties, as the destruction of a single nest can kill up to 400 females and young, thus risk destroying an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish Project Manager for the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to lend a hand.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we have, we don't know how the populations are developing."
